For anyone who was unable to import joblib, you're probably using a more recent version, where joblib comes separated from sklearn. Instead of this line:
from sklearn.externals import joblib
try:
from joblib import dump, load
Then instead of:
joblib.dump(model, 'music_recommender.joblib')
Use:
dump(model, 'music_recommender.joblib')

I think this is the first set of AI created ‚Äúart‚Äù images that give me hope for artists‚Ä¶ as this is the first set that reveals the limitations of the software, rather than wows me due to my apparent ignorance of the source material. I‚Äôm a huge Terminator fan, and virtually none of these are as good as James Cameron‚Äôs intelligently crafted concept art. There‚Äôs little that‚Äôs impressive about these images. There‚Äôs no logic to them. The terrifying thing about the Terminator concept is how, underneath the nightmarish imagery, there‚Äôs nothing but cold, machine-like, efficiency. Virtually none of these machines would pass for human. The only legitimately ‚Äúgood‚Äù image occurs near the end; just before the actual T2 footage. A better name for Artificial Intelligence would be Illusory Intelligence, because it can only provide the illusion of expressed thought. ‚ÄúThinking‚Äù, even artificially, would be too strong a word to describe what‚Äôs going on under the hood of these AI art calculators. I enjoy some AI art (I mean, it‚Äôs fun), but, as someone incredibly familiar with the making of the James Cameron Terminator films, this set just reveals how remarkably unintelligent AI art generation actually is.

'Certainly! Pasta allo scarpariello is a classic Italian pasta dish that's simple yet flavorful. Here's a recipe for four servings using the Italian cooking method:

Ingredients:

400g of pasta (penne or rigatoni)

4 tablespoons of olive oil

3 cloves of garlic, minced

1/4 teaspoon of red pepper flakes

4 anchovy fillets, chopped

1/2 cup of white wine

2 cups of cherry tomatoes, halved

1/2 cup of chopped parsley

1/2 cup of grated Parmesan cheese

Salt and pepper to taste

Instructions:

Begin by bringing a large pot of salted water to a boil. Add the pasta and cook according to the package instructions until al dente.

While the pasta cooks, heat the olive oil in a large pan over medium heat. Add the minced garlic, red pepper flakes, and anchovy fillets. Cook until the garlic is fragrant and the anchovies have melted into the oil.

Pour in the white wine and bring to a simmer. Let the mixture cook for 2-3 minutes, until the alcohol has evaporated and the liquid has reduced slightly.

Add the halved cherry tomatoes to the pan and cook for another 2-3 minutes, until the tomatoes have softened and released their juices.

Drain the pasta and add it to the pan with the tomato sauce. Toss everything together until the pasta is coated in the sauce.

Stir in the chopped parsley and grated Parmesan cheese. Season with salt and pepper to taste.

Serve the pasta allo scarpariello hot, garnished with extra Parmesan cheese and chopped parsley, if desired.

Enjoy your delicious and authentic Italian pasta allo scarpariello!'

Great videoI'll stick with Eva's real intelligence and recipesIt seems that AI didn't get it rightI think it tried to interpret the individual words, rather than looking at the title of the recipe, pasta allo scarpariello, as a phrase with a specific meaning. AI might have misinterpreted pasta allo scarpariello, confusing or connecting the word scarpariello with the word scallopini. This might explain both the connection with pork, and the reason why the directions said to chop the sausage. It might also have viewed the pasta as a side or an 'add in'; which is why AI said to cook it first, and then set it aside. For example, you can have sausage scallopini with or without pasta. I also think it missed a nuance of meaning between the word minced, and idea of what it means to finely chop. To mince means to chop or cut a small as possible, it's specific. To finely chop, however, can mean to mince, but it could also mean something as different as julienne. Overall, AI didn't seem to be very good at handling the idea of a recipe.

what do you think of this recipe
Osso Buco alla Milanese
 
Ingredients:
 
4 veal shanks, about 1 inch thick, tied with kitchen twine
Salt and freshly ground black pepper
1/2 cup all-purpose flour, for dredging
1/4 cup unsalted butter
1/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil
1 onion, finely chopped
1 carrot, finely chopped
1 celery stalk, finely chopped
2 garlic cloves, minced
1 tablespoon tomato paste
1 1/2 cups chicken broth
1 1/2 cups dry white wine
1 bay leaf
1 sprig fresh thyme
1 sprig fresh rosemary
Grated zest of 1 lemon
Gremolata (recipe below)
Risotto alla Milanese (recipe below)
Directions:
 
Preheat the oven to 350¬∞F.
 
Season the veal shanks with salt and pepper, and dredge them in the flour, shaking off any excess.
 
In a large Dutch oven or ovenproof pot, melt the butter with the olive oil over medium-high heat. When the butter is foamy, add the veal shanks and cook, turning occasionally, until browned on all sides, about 10 minutes.
 
Transfer the veal shanks to a plate and set aside.
 
Add the onion, carrot, celery, and garlic to the pot and saut√© until the vegetables are softened, about 5 minutes.
 
Stir in the tomato paste and cook for 1 minute.
 
Add the chicken broth, white wine, bay leaf, thyme, rosemary, and lemon zest, and bring to a simmer.
 
Return the veal shanks to the pot and spoon some of the vegetables and sauce over the top.
 
Cover the pot and transfer it to the oven. Bake until the meat is very tender and falls off the bone, about 2 1/2 hours.
 
To serve, remove the veal shanks from the pot and discard the kitchen twine. Serve each veal shank over a bed of risotto alla Milanese (recipe below), and sprinkle with gremolata (recipe below).
 
Gremolata:
 
1/4 cup finely chopped fresh parsley
1 garlic clove, minced
Grated zest of 1 lemon
Combine all ingredients in a small bowl.
 
Risotto alla Milanese:
 
4 cups chicken broth
4 tablespoons unsalted butter
1 onion, finely chopped
2 cups Arborio rice
1/2 cup dry white wine
1/2 teaspoon saffron threads
1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese
Salt and freshly ground black pepper
In a medium saucepan, bring the chicken broth to a simmer.
 
In a large saucepan, melt the butter over medium-high heat. Add the onion and saut√© until softened, about 5 minutes.
 
Add the rice and stir to coat with the butter.
 
Add the white wine and stir until it is absorbed.
 
Add the saffron to the hot chicken broth and stir to dissolve.
 
Add a ladleful of hot broth to the rice and stir until it is absorbed.
 
Continue adding the broth, one ladleful at a time, stirring constantly and allowing each addition to be absorbed before adding the next, until the rice is tender and creamy

There is a way you can knead that watery semolina dough, called the coil fold method. When you start you're certain it will never work, but after a lot of folding with multiple rests in between, it does. The issue is that semola/semolina, while high in protein generally, is low in the specific kinds of protein that form gluten, so you have to really work (or give a longer time to) the gluten-producing proteins it does have. You'll never get anything close to traditional bread dough, but you'll eventually get to something recognizable as dough.

I agree that canned diced tomatoes are not ideal. They're almost always treated with calcium chloride, which helps the tomato retain its firmness during the canning process. This is great if you're making something where you want the tomatoes to have some "raw" characteristic to them, like bruschetta or pico de gallo. But calcium chloride is too good at its job. Even if you simmer a sauce for half an hour, the tomatoes won't break down. And if you throw them in a blender, they come out kind of mealy.

This isn't a brand thing. If you look at the ingredients for any major brand of canned tomatoes, the diced tomatoes will almost always include calcium chloride, while the crushed and whole varieties from that same brand probably won't.

Ingredienti:

Preparazione:

Quando la cipolla diventa trasparente, aggiungi i pomodori pelati spezzettati con le mani e un po' di sale. Lascia cuocere a fuoco medio-basso per circa 10 minuti, fino a quando la salsa diventa densa e il liquido si √® evaporato.

Sfuma con il vino bianco e lascia evaporare l'alcol.
Scolare la pasta e uniscila alla padella con la salsa e il pollo. Aggiungi il prezzemolo tritato e mescola bene.

Chiedo scusa per l'errore, hai ragione. La pasta allo scarpariello tradizionale non prevede l'uso del pollo tra gli ingredienti. Ecco la ricetta corretta:

Ingredienti:

400 g di pasta corta (come penne o rigatoni)
500 g di pomodori pelati
2 spicchi di aglio
1 peperoncino rosso (facoltativo)
1 cipolla
1 mazzetto di prezzemolo fresco
1/2 bicchiere di vino bianco
Olio extravergine di oliva q.b.
Sale e pepe q.b.
Preparazione:

Inizia preparando la salsa. Trita la cipolla e l'aglio e mettili a soffriggere in una padella con un po' di olio extravergine di oliva. Aggiungi il peperoncino rosso se desideri un po' di piccante.
Quando la cipolla diventa trasparente, aggiungi i pomodori pelati spezzettati con le mani e un po' di sale. Lascia cuocere a fuoco medio-basso per circa 10 minuti, fino a quando la salsa diventa densa e il liquido si √® evaporato.
Nel frattempo, cuoci la pasta in abbondante acqua salata seguendo le istruzioni sulla confezione fino a quando √® al dente.
Scolare la pasta e unirla alla padella con la salsa. Aggiungi il prezzemolo tritato e mescola bene.
Sfuma con il vino bianco e lascia evaporare l'alcol.
Servi la pasta allo scarpariello calda con una spolverata di pepe e se lo desideri una manciata di parmigiano grattugiato.
Buon appetito!

Spicy Habanero and Pineapple Pasta

Ingredients:

1 pound of pasta (penne or rigatoni works well)
2 habanero peppers, seeded and finely chopped
1/2 cup of fresh pineapple juice
1/4 cup of extra-virgin olive oil
1/4 cup of grated Pecorino Romano cheese
2 garlic cloves, minced
Salt and pepper to taste
Directions:

Cook the pasta in a large pot of boiling salted water according to package instructions until al dente.

While the pasta is cooking, heat the olive oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the chopped habanero peppers and garlic, and saut√© for about 2-3 minutes until fragrant.

Pour in the pineapple juice and bring to a simmer. Let the sauce cook for 5-6 minutes until it has slightly thickened and reduced.

Once the pasta is cooked, reserve about 1/2 cup of the pasta cooking water, then drain the pasta and add it to the skillet with the habanero pineapple sauce. Toss the pasta to coat it evenly with the sauce.

If the sauce is too thick, add some of the reserved pasta water to loosen it up. Season with salt and pepper to taste.

Data scientists are primarily responsible for analysing and interpreting complex data sets to derive insights and inform business decisions. They use a range of statistical and machine learning techniques to process, clean, and transform data, and they often work with large, messy, and unstructured data sets. Data scientists are skilled in programming languages such as Python and R, as well as data visualization tools such as Tableau.
 
AI engineers, on the other hand, are primarily responsible for developing and implementing the algorithms and models that power artificial intelligence systems. They design, build, and train machine learning models and neural networks, and they deploy these models in production environments to power AI applications. AI engineers are skilled in programming languages such as Python, Java, and C++, as well as in tools and frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
 
In summary, while data scientists focus on analysing data to derive insights, AI engineers focus on building and deploying artificial intelligence systems.

**Summary**:
- machine learning is the general term for when computers learn from data
- there are lots of different ways ("algorithms") that machines can learn 
- the algorithms can be grouped into supervised, unsupervised, and reinforcement algorithms*

- the data that you feed to a machine learning algorithm can be input-output pairs or just inputs
- supervised learning algorithms require input-output pairs (i.e. they require the output)
- unsupervised learning requires only the input data (not the outputs)

- here is how, in general, supervised algorithms work:
- you feed it an example input, then the associated output
- you repeat the above step many many times
- eventually, the algorithm picks up a pattern between the inputs and outputs
- now, you can feed it a brand new input, and it will predict the output for you

- here is how, in general, unsupervised algorithms work:
- you feed it an example input (without the associated output)
- you repeat the above step many times
- eventually, the algorithm clusters your inputs into groups
- now, you can feed it a brand new input, and the algorithm will predict which cluster it belongs with

* the first example in this video used the k-nearest neighbor algorithm, which is a supervised machine learning algorithm

Hope that was useful to someone!

Scenario 1: Facebook recognizes your friend in a picture from an album of tagged photographs
Explanation: It is supervised learning. Here Facebook is using tagged photos to recognize the person. Therefore, the tagged photos become the labels of the pictures and we know that when the machine is learning from labelled data, it is supervised learning.

Scenario 2: Recommending new songs based on someone‚Äôs past music choices
Explanation: It is supervised learning. The model is training a classifier on pre-existing labels (genres of songs).
This is what Netflix, Pandora, and Spotify do all the time, they collect the songs/movies that you like already, evaluate the features based on your likes/dislikes and then recommend new movies/songs based on similar features.

Scenario 3: Analyze bank data for suspicious looking transactions and flag the fraud transactions
Explanation: It is unsupervised learning. In this case, the suspicious transactions are not defined, hence there are no labels of "fraud" and "not fraud". The model tries to identify outliers by looking at anomalous transactions and flags them as 'fraud'.

scenario1 is supervised ) (scenario 2 unsupervised) (scenario 3 is reinforcement)

Senario one= reinforcement learning, Senario 2= unsupervised learning and scenario 3 = supervised learning. 

In scenario 1 you try to find the name of your friend for example, but after you searched it on Facebook, you'll see that many members has exact the same name. Thus, you give feedback to use the filter-model of it in order to find the correct person with the correct characteristics. That's why the first one is Reinforcement Learning. 

2nd scenario, when you want to find the movie on Netflix which you like, you'll see that there so many movies you like to watch. However, you just want to focus on the quality of the movie ( like the tempo, the resolution, audio accuracy) although you do not know the label. That's why it is unsupervised. 

Finally, the last one is supervised because you know that in your computer there are intruders, like viruses or hackers, which can be detected based on the model it's designed to find the feature, which the degree of danger, and the label, which is a virus, hackers, spyware, and many more.

I think the answer to the quiz is 1) Supervised learning 2) Unsupervised learning 3) Reinforced learning.¬†

1st scenario doesn't need to be explained because it is pretty straightforward. Images with certain characteristics are tagged with a person's name. So the input and the output are clearly defined. In 2nd scenario, the system compiles a list of all songs/tv shows which a user has liked. It recognises tag/metadata that occurs repeatedly/ frequently in the compiled list (e.g. genre, language, category, etc). It suggests songs/tv shows which match the frequently occurring metadata/tag. So here the system just compiled the liked list and did pattern matching without any input from a person. So I think it is unsupervised learning. 

In the 3rd scenario, I believe the system brings up transactions that are outliers or that match specific criteria (e.g. amount above a certain number, frequency of transactions, location, and more complicated variables obviously). Then these transactions are manually evaluated by a human and filed under 'fraud' or 'not fraud' category. The machine learns to distinguish micro patterns or subtle differences and eventually after enough repetition and feedback loop, is able to more accurately distinguish fraudulent transactions from the non fraudulent ones. Here the systems initial actions are further reinforced by a human, thereby improving the accuracy of the process, hence reinforced learning.

How is scenario 2 supervised? The machine is learning a pattern (what movies does user watch), but there is no feedback since the user does not tell the machine yes I like it or no I don't. You could say there is feedback if they watch a recommended movie, but the user will ignore the vast majority of recommendations. That is no feedback, since they COULD watch it later, they are just not interested AT THE MOMENT. Labeling a recommendation as wrong would be arbitrary at any given point in time.

Rules:
1. Any time the AI starts to repeat itself, that's passage is removed.
2. The DM decides what to type so that the AI can account for all possible factors with minimal bias.
3. Technology cannot exceed the world leader in a given area by more than a single step.
4. The DM should be tough but fair with regard to geographically insane invasion plans.
5. If the AI tries to make a premature conclusion to the game by giving someone the entire world, that paragraph or sentence is removed.
6. AI nations are mapped too, and do not have to follow the rules about using only resources they explicitly have or troops they explicitly have. If suddenly the Mongols appear with 250000 troops, that's what happens. They still need to follow the tech rules.
7. If the AI says something completely inconsistent with the map, reroll that round. Note however that something like part of an existing empire rebelling or there being continued resistance in an area after it's been conquered is completely reasonable.

I was reading about Sanskrit last weekend. Wild. Humanity's first baby steps at developing a refined language around 2,000 B.C. It's the language used in the Rig Veda (World's oldest religious text). Someone named Panini later wrote a guide on what was thought to provide all the parts of the language (roots, prefixes, and suffixes). He classified some 2,000 monosyllabic roots. We find a lot of these parts in Western languages such as "matr" = "mother". 

As Kyla says, language is foundational because it's how we interact with each other. I think we're continuously craving each other and there's this language barrier or checkpoint that we have to go through to connect. The problem is if you don't structure the sentence right or the tone is off or if one language rule is broken it's like "connect request denied". When this starts happening I say let's just create a new language. Panini did it. Why can't we?

Attempting to describe and exhaust reality, as if we could control it, through language might distract us from the fact that we are much more clueless and unconscious than we give ourselves credit for. The best friends I've found in life spoke in some distinct way, behaved, carried themselves, made choices, that I'm too dumb to put words too; maybe I'm too slow to consciously grasp and keep up with all the unspoken, intuitive, cues. Technology, and their design, play a role into those cues; they have a will of their own. On the other hand, "social media," "artificial intelligence," in our collective, immediate understanding do not have in their meanings all of their potential. Think of "smartphones" - before and after the commercial success of the iPhone, what the average person would describe as a phone being "smart" was totally different. Social media, as we see it today, depends a lot in the success and paradigms set by Facebook. AI is heavily used for ads in some business model, in some capitalistic society, in some historical setting.  As someone reads this comment they see my name up there; a profile, a potential reputation; an "avatar" of my sense of self. That is a design choice. You didn't necessarily have to be able to see this comment, or see who wrote it, or how much people liked it, answered it. All of these design choices inform behavior and expected rewards. What if there were no profiles? What if the definition of what "engagement" is was radically different? What if algorithms didn't optimize for engagement at all? Technology could provide platforms to help solve the problem of loneliness, even if we agree that their current design accentuate it. AI could be built for enhancing serendipity.

The existential conversation is dominated by save the polar bears and stop boiling oceans and nuclear war and a.I.
The  conversation forgot that if 2 generations have 1 child per couple then the population declines -80%

One contributing factor is locality-rooted community has diminished to almost nothing

 there‚Äôs a better way however Unlikely it will be built and scaled before a large population decline.  

Perhaps new zoning laws to restructure the physical world to re-orient people for locality-rooted community. Perhaps new cultural standards (regulation?) for tech usage. Akin to cigarettes.

Both Bill and Elon are people who understands the concepts and complications of AI and softwares and how technology works at its core. I've worked a little bit on AI and can offer a bit of perspective:

For the most part, the skepticism in the machine learning community comes from the fact that it's *extremely difficult to devise a general intelligence algorithm akin to that of our minds. It is not only a theoretical problem (i.e. binary 1s and 0s interpreting meaning and drawing conclusions), it is also a hardware problem, although that is slowly being solved. 

If such an algorithm can be created, it will need enormous amounts of training data in order to be operable. 

The inherent dangers are more perceptible to those at the fringes of AI research than at its frontier, for the perceived difficulty is more visceral in the doing than in its observation. This partly explains the bullish attitude Google, Baidu, and Facebook has undertaken. 

At least in my view, the dangers of AI are non-trivial in its eventuality IF it came to pass. For most part, the magnitude of fallouts of technologies coincides with their benefit. If this axiom holds, the potential downside of AI could potentially be catastrophic, but such a thing is very difficult to forecast.
